%S A397698 81,32,32,64,54,64,27,81,96,160,112,512,135,144,125,160,176,128,192,
%T A397698 320,216,224,243,243,256,256,272,128,729,320,351,320,336,384,352,736,
%U A397698 375,384,392,640,416,432,243,448,405,486,472,448,496,560,512,512,513,544,552
%N A397698 a(n) is obtained by inserting exactly one decimal digit into the decimal expansion of n. Among all resulting integers m, maximize k such that p^k | m. If more than one choice attains the same maximum exponent k, choose the one with the largest prime p.
%C A397698 If more than one of the resulting integers has the same k and p, choose the smallest.
%C A397698 It is disallowed to prepend the digit "0" as a leading digit.
%C A397698 Since we can add one trailing digit to any number and make it a multiple of 8, the power k is always >= 3.
%H A397698 Michael S. Branicky, <a href="/A397698/b397698.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%F A397698 For n = 2^i, i > 4, a(n) = 10*n.
%e A397698 a(1) = 81, since 81 = 3^4 and 16 = 2^4; both have exponent 4, but 3 > 2.
%e A397698 a(5) = 54, since 54 = 2*3^3.
%e A397698 a(13) = 135, since 135 = 3^3*5 and 513 = 3^3*19; both have k=p=3 but 135 < 513.
%o A397698 (Python)
%o A397698 from sympy import factorint
%o A397698 def f(n): return max((k, p) for p, k in factorint(n).items())
%o A397698 def cands(s): yield from map(int, set(s[:i]+d+s[i:] for i in range(len(s)+1) for d in "0123456789"[int(i==0):]))
%o A397698 def a(n): return -sorted(f(t)+(-t, ) for t in cands(str(n)))[-1][2]
%o A397698 print([a(n) for n in range(1, 56)]) # _Michael S. Branicky_, Jul 05 2026
